Getting Started with BulkS4

Hui Ouyang

2025-05-24

Source: vignettes/getting-started.Rmd
getting-started.Rmd

Introduction

BulkS4 is a comprehensive R package designed for bulk RNA-seq data analysis using S4 classes. This package provides a unified framework for storing, analyzing, and visualizing bulk RNA-seq data, including:

  • Differential expression analysis using DESeq2, edgeR, and limma-voom
  • Gene set enrichment analysis (GSEA)
  • Gene set variation analysis (GSVA)
  • Integrated data management with S4 classes

Installation 

# Install from GitHub
devtools::install_github("HUI950319/BulkS4")

Loading the Package 

library(BulkS4)
#> 
#> Warning: multiple methods tables found for 'gsva'

Quick Start

Loading Example Data

BulkS4 comes with example datasets that you can use to get started:

# Load example datasets
data(counts)      # RNA-seq count matrix
data(metadata)    # Sample metadata
data(geneSet_msig) # MSigDB gene sets

# Examine the data
head(counts[, 1:6])
#>          Cov1 Cov2 Cov3 Mock1 Mock2 Mock3
#> TSPAN6   1270 1013  848  4571  5500  4844
#> TNMD      121  125   49  3220  6435  2977
#> DPM1     1023 1045  674  2404  4794  1819
#> SCYL3    1049  713  692   854   356  1015
#> C1orf112  211  158   90   576   195   477
#> FGR         9    8    2    10     5     0
head(metadata)
#>       sample group
#> Cov1    Cov1 treat
#> Cov2    Cov2 treat
#> Cov3    Cov3 treat
#> Mock1  Mock1   con
#> Mock2  Mock2   con
#> Mock3  Mock3   con

Creating a BulkRNAseq Object

The core of BulkS4 is the BulkRNAseq S4 class, which stores all your RNA-seq data and analysis results:

# Create BulkRNAseq object
bulk_obj <- BulkRNAseq(counts, metadata)
#> Successfully loaded MSigDB gene sets from package data

# View the object
bulk_obj
#> 
#>  ====== BulkRNAseq Object ====== 
#> 
#> Genes:          36888
#> Samples:        6
#> Metadata vars:  sample, group
#> 
#>  ------ Analysis Results ------ 
#> 
#> Diff analyses:  0: None
#> Gene sets:      25: C1, C2_CGP, C2_CP, C2_CP:BIOCARTA, C2_CP:KEGG_LEGACY, C2_CP:KEGG_MEDICUS, C2_CP:PID, C2_CP:REACTOME, C2_CP:WIKIPATHWAYS, C3_MIR:MIRDB, C3_MIR:MIR_LEGACY, C3_TFT:GTRD, C3_TFT:TFT_LEGACY, C4_3CA, C4_CGN, C4_CM, C5_GO:BP, C5_GO:CC, C5_GO:MF, C5_HPO, C6, C7_IMMUNESIGDB, C7_VAX, C8, H
#> GSEA results:   0: None
#> GSVA results:   0: None
#> 
#>  --------------------------------------------------

Basic Operations 

# Get dimensions
dim(bulk_obj)
#> [1] 36888     6

# Get gene and sample names
head(rownames(bulk_obj))
#> [1] "TSPAN6"   "TNMD"     "DPM1"     "SCYL3"    "C1orf112" "FGR"
colnames(bulk_obj)
#> [1] "Cov1"  "Cov2"  "Cov3"  "Mock1" "Mock2" "Mock3"

# Access metadata columns
head(bulk_obj$group)
#> [1] treat treat treat con   con   con  
#> Levels: con treat

Data Access 

# Get raw counts
raw_counts <- getCounts(bulk_obj)
dim(raw_counts)
#> [1] 36888     6

# Get normalized data (initially same as counts)
norm_data <- getData(bulk_obj)

# Get metadata
sample_meta <- getMetadata(bulk_obj)
str(sample_meta)
#> 'data.frame':    6 obs. of  2 variables:
#>  $ sample: chr  "Cov1" "Cov2" "Cov3" "Mock1" ...
#>  $ group : Factor w/ 2 levels "con","treat": 2 2 2 1 1 1

Data Manipulation 

# Set normalized data (log2 transformation)
log_counts <- log2(getCounts(bulk_obj) + 1)
bulk_obj <- setData(bulk_obj, log_counts)

# Verify the change
head(getData(bulk_obj)[, 1:3])
#>               Cov1      Cov2     Cov3
#> TSPAN6   10.311748  9.985842 9.729621
#> TNMD      6.930737  6.977280 5.643856
#> DPM1     10.000000 10.030667 9.398744
#> SCYL3    10.036174  9.479780 9.436712
#> C1orf112  7.727920  7.312883 6.507795
#> FGR       3.321928  3.169925 1.584963

Subsetting 

# Subset to first 100 genes and first 6 samples
subset_obj <- bulk_obj[1:100, 1:6]
dim(subset_obj)
#> [1] 100   6
